# CaptionDB Coding Standards Contract

## Purpose

This document defines the mandatory coding standards for the CaptionDB project.

Every source file generated for this repository must follow these standards.

These standards take precedence over convenience.

---

# General Philosophy

Every line of code should be:

- Readable
- Predictable
- Testable
- Maintainable
- Extensible
- Explicit

Code is written for humans first and computers second.

---

# General Rules

Always write production-quality code.

Never write demo-quality code.

Never sacrifice readability for brevity.

Prefer clarity over cleverness.

Avoid premature optimization.

Optimize only after correctness.

---

# Supported Languages

Backend

- Python 3.12+

Frontend

- TypeScript
- React
- Vite

---

# Naming Conventions

## Variables

Use descriptive names.

Good

video_processor

scene_detector

caption_request

Bad

tmp

obj

data1

value

---

## Functions

Use verbs.

Good

generate_caption()

extract_frames()

detect_scenes()

validate_request()

Bad

caption()

frames()

scene()

---

## Classes

Use PascalCase.

Good

FireworksClient

CaptionGenerator

SceneDetector

PromptManager

---

## Constants

Use UPPER_CASE.

Example

DEFAULT_TIMEOUT

MAX_FRAME_COUNT

CACHE_DIRECTORY

---

## Files

Use snake_case.

Examples

scene_detector.py

caption_generator.py

prompt_manager.py

---

## React Components

Use PascalCase.

Examples

Sidebar.tsx

VideoPlayer.tsx

ExportDialog.tsx

---

# Function Design

Functions should perform one responsibility.

Avoid long functions.

Target:

20–40 lines

Refactor when complexity increases.

---

# Class Design

Classes should have one responsibility.

Large classes should be split.

Prefer composition over inheritance.

---

# Type Safety

Python

Always use type hints.

Every parameter.

Every return value.

Avoid Any unless absolutely necessary.

TypeScript

Never use any.

Prefer unknown if required.

Use strict typing.

---

# Data Models

Never pass raw dictionaries through the application.

Use:

Pydantic models

Dataclasses

Typed interfaces

Domain models

---

# Imports

Order imports as:

1. Standard Library

2. Third-party Packages

3. Internal Modules

Separate each group with a blank line.

Never use wildcard imports.

Example

from module import *

is prohibited.

---

# Magic Numbers

Never use magic numbers.

Bad

timeout = 17

Good

timeout = settings.api_timeout

---

# Hardcoded Values

Never hardcode:

API keys

URLs

Paths

Model IDs

Temperatures

Retry counts

Timeouts

Frame counts

Thresholds

Prompt text

Style names

Everything belongs in configuration.

---

# Comments

Write comments only when necessary.

Explain WHY.

Do not explain WHAT.

Bad

Increment i

Good

Retry to handle temporary API rate limits.

---

# Docstrings

Every public:

Function

Class

Method

Module

must include docstrings.

Use Google style.

Include:

Purpose

Arguments

Returns

Raises

---

# Error Handling

Never ignore exceptions.

Never suppress exceptions.

Never use:

except:
    pass

Catch specific exceptions.

Raise meaningful custom exceptions.

Always log unexpected failures.

---

# Logging

Never use print().

Use structured logging.

Log:

Entry

Exit

Duration

Warnings

Errors

Retries

Important decisions

Never log:

Secrets

API Keys

Tokens

Passwords

Sensitive data

---

# Async Rules

Use async only when appropriate.

Network operations

Async

CPU intensive tasks

Use worker threads or appropriate executors.

Do not mix sync and async incorrectly.

---

# Code Duplication

Avoid duplication.

If logic appears twice

extract it.

Prefer reusable utilities.

---

# Dependency Injection

Never instantiate shared services inside business logic.

Receive dependencies through constructors or FastAPI dependency injection.

---

# Configuration

Every configurable value belongs in:

Environment variables

Configuration files

Settings

Never inside business logic.

---

# Validation

Validate every external input.

Never trust:

User input

API responses

File contents

JSON

Environment variables

Validate before processing.

---

# Security

Never trust filenames.

Never trust paths.

Never trust MIME types.

Never expose internal exceptions directly.

Never expose stack traces to users.

---

# Performance

Avoid unnecessary loops.

Avoid unnecessary copies.

Reuse expensive resources.

Cache when beneficial.

Measure before optimizing.

---

# API Responses

Use strongly typed response models.

Never return inconsistent structures.

All responses should be predictable.

---

# File Size

Prefer small focused files.

Avoid files larger than approximately 500 lines unless there is a clear architectural justification.

Split responsibilities instead of creating monolithic modules.

---

# Function Parameters

Avoid long parameter lists.

Prefer configuration objects or typed models.

---

# Testing

Every new feature should include:

Unit tests

Edge case tests

Failure tests

Integration tests when applicable

---

# Documentation

Whenever implementation changes behavior:

Update documentation.

Update README if required.

Update API specification if required.

---

# TODO Policy

TODOs are allowed only when:

Waiting for external dependency

Waiting for official documentation

Waiting for future implementation

Every TODO must explain:

Why

Owner

Expected future work

---

# Code Review Checklist

Before finalizing implementation verify:

✓ No hardcoded values

✓ No duplicated code

✓ Proper typing

✓ Proper naming

✓ Proper logging

✓ Proper exception handling

✓ Documentation added

✓ Configuration driven

✓ Tests added

✓ Imports organized

✓ Security considered

✓ Performance reviewed

✓ Compatible with existing architecture

If any check fails, revise the implementation before completion.

---

End of Coding Standards Contract.
